\begin_layout Enumerate
Recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $(AB)^{T}=B^{T}A^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I=I^{T}=(AA^{-1})^{T}=(A^{-1})^{T}A^{T}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(A^{T})^{-1}=(A^{-1})^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{-1}A\vec{x}=\lambda\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=A^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=B^{*}\succ0$
\end_inset

 (positive-definite), then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\langle\vec{x},B^{-1}A\vec{x}\rangle_{B} & = & \langle\vec{x},\lambda\vec{x}\rangle_{B}=\lambda(\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{x})\\
 & = & \vec{x}^{*}B(B^{-1}A\vec{x})=\vec{x}^{*}AB^{-1}B\vec{x}=(B^{-1}A\vec{x})^{*}B\vec{x}=\bar{\lambda}(\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{x}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where in the second-to-last step we used the facts that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}=A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(B^{-1})^{*}=B^{-1}$
\end_inset

 [from part (a)].
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $B\succ0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\neq0$
\end_inset

 (eigenvectors are not zero), 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{x}>0$
\end_inset

, and we can divide by it to get 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=\bar{\lambda}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is real.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

If we have a second eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{-1}A\vec{y}=\mu\vec{y}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\neq\mu$
\end_inset

, then we just take the dot product of both sides with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 to obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\langle\vec{x},B^{-1}A\vec{y}\rangle_{B} & = & \langle\vec{x},\mu\vec{y}\rangle_{B}=\mu(\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{y})\\
 & = & \vec{x}^{*}B(B^{-1}A\vec{y})=\vec{x}^{*}AB^{-1}B\vec{y}=(B^{-1}A\vec{x})^{*}B\vec{y}=\lambda(\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{y}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu-\lambda)(\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{y})=0,$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}^{*}B\vec{y}=\langle\vec{x},\vec{y}\rangle_{B}=0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 they are orthogonal under this inner product.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(You have to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

