\begin_layout Standard
We consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d^{2}}{dx^{2}}u(x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\emph on
quasiperiodic
\emph default
 boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=e^{i\phi}u(L)$
\end_inset

 for some real number 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Erratum: I really should have specified 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(0)=e^{i\phi}u'(L)$
\end_inset

 as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As in class, the eigenfunctions of second derivatives are sines, cosines,
 and exponentials.
 If you go through the three different possibilities, you end up trying
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=e^{ikx}$
\end_inset

, which have eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $-k^{2}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $u''=-k^{2}u$
\end_inset

.
 The only question is whether we can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to satisfy the boundary conditions.
 (You could also do 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{\alpha x}$
\end_inset

, in which case you would find an imaginary 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

.) From 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=1=e^{i\phi}u(L)=e^{ikL+i\phi}$
\end_inset

, we immediately find that 
\begin_inset Formula $k=-\phi/L$
\end_inset

 works.
