We could also say that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ikL}=e^{-i\phi}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\log(e^{-i\phi})/iL$
\end_inset

, and then remember that the complex logarithm is multi-valued (you can
 add any multiplie of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi i$
\end_inset

 to the result).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is that if we add any integer multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi/L$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, it doesn't change the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ikL}$
\end_inset

.
 So, the allowed solutions are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{n}(x)=e^{i(\frac{2\pi n}{L}-\frac{\phi}{L})x}
\]

\end_inset

for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (including 
\begin_inset Formula $n\text{\le0}$
\end_inset

), and the eigenvalues are 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}=-\frac{(2\pi n-\phi)^{2}}{L^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

If you also got 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin(n\pi x/L)$
\end_inset

, this is my fault for not specifying the quasiperiodicity of 
\begin_inset Formula $u'$
\end_inset

 as well as of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We don't have unique solutions when there is a nontrivial nullspace, which
 corresponds to having one or more zero eigenvalues.
 From above, that only occurs for 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=2\pi n$
\end_inset

, in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As in class, the key to doing problems like this is to expand the right-hand-sid
e in the basis of the eigenfunctions, i.e., try to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\sum_{n}c_{n}e^{i(\frac{2\pi n}{L}-\frac{\phi}{L})x}
\]

\end_inset

for some coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 But if we move the 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 factor to the left-hand side, this is 
\emph on
exactly
\emph default
 the same as an ordinary Fourier series for 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)e^{i\phi x/L}=\sum_{n}c_{n}e^{i\frac{2\pi n}{L}x},
\]

\end_inset

which converges (almost everywhere), from class, whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\int|f(x)e^{i\phi x/L}|^{1+\epsilon}=\int|f(x)|^{1+\epsilon}<\infty$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

; thanks to the absolute values, this is equivalent to the condition for
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 to have a convergent Fourier series.
 So, we can do this expansion.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In terms of this expansion, formally writing 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\hat{A}^{-1}f(x)$
\end_inset

, we can just divide each term in the series by the corresponding eigenvalue,
 as in class, to obtain a solution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x)=\sum_{n}\frac{c_{n}}{\lambda_{n}}e^{i(\frac{2\pi n}{L}-\frac{\phi}{L})x}.
\]

\end_inset

The only case in which this would 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 work is if we divided by zero, i.e.
 some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, there is no solution 
\emph on
unless
\emph default
 we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{n}=0$
\end_inset

: if that term is missing from the 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 series, we never divide by zero.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

So, in summary, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 has a convergent Fourier series, a solution exists if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\neq2\pi n$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\emph on
or
\emph default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=2\pi n$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c_{n}=0=\frac{1}{L}\int_{0}^{L}f(x)e^{-i(\frac{2\pi n}{L}-\frac{\phi}{L})x}dx,
\]

\end_inset

where for the last expression I used the explicit formula for the Fourier
 series coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)e^{i\phi x/L}$
\end_inset

 (or, later on, we will equivalently think of this as arising from the orthogona
lity of eigenfunctions of a Hermitian operator).
